---

Wash and dry produce.

Dice @sweet potatoes{1} into 1⁄2-inch pieces. Place in a large #microwave-safe bowl{} and cover with #plastic wrap{}. Microwave until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}. (You'll finish the sweet potato in Step 5.)

Meanwhile, trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; slice crosswise into 1⁄2-inch-thick half-moons. Halve, peel, and slice @red onion{1} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges.

In a #small bowl{} combine @Vidalia onion paste{1%ounce}, @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, half the @maple syrup{2%tablespoon}, and @water{2%TBSP} (all the maple syrup and 4 TBSP water for 4 servings). Season with @pepper{}.

Pat @salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; place between two large pieces of plastic wrap. Pound with a #mallet{} or #rolling pin{} until salmon is about 1⁄2 inch thick. Lightly season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Swap in salmon for chicken (no need to pound salmon!). Cook (skin sides down) until skin is crisp, 5-7 minutes. Flip and cook until cooked through, 1-2 minutes more. Turn salmon in pan with maple Dijon sauce as instructed.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add salmon; cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

Remove pan from heat. Add maple Dijon sauce and @butter{1%TBSP} (2 TBSP for 4 servings), stirring until butter has melted and turning salmon to evenly coat.

> TIP: If sauce seems too thick, add a splash or two of water.

While salmon cooks, heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a second large pan over medium-high heat. Add sweet potato, zucchini, and onion wedges; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Cook, stirring, until softened and lightly browned, ~{5-7%minutes} (7-10 minutes for 4 servings).

Divide vegetable jumble between #plates{} or #shallow bowls{}. Top with salmon. Spoon any remaining maple Dijon sauce from pan over salmon and vegetables. Serve.

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.